00:00:05.170 --> 00:00:07.779
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: Hi, everybody. Thank
you all for joining us today.

00:00:07.779 --> 00:00:11.390
Garance DorÃ© began her career as an illustrator
living in

00:00:11.390 --> 00:00:15.309
Paris. And in 2006, she began her blog Une
Fille Comme

00:00:15.309 --> 00:00:17.740
Moi where she publishes her drawings and musings
about

00:00:17.740 --> 00:00:21.420
life. Garance picked up a camera and began
adding

00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:24.272
street-style photographs to her blog and the
rest as they

00:00:24.272 --> 00:00:27.480
say is fashion history. So please join me
in welcoming

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:29.289
Garance to New York.

00:00:29.289 --> 00:00:30.289
[Applause]

00:00:30.289 --> 00:00:31.930
&gt;&gt;Garance: Hi.

00:00:31.930 --> 00:00:36.841
&gt;&gt;Presenter: So Garance thank you so much
for coming here. We're

00:00:36.841 --> 00:00:40.710
very thrilled to have you. As we'll discuss
later, we're

00:00:40.710 --> 00:00:44.720
not necessarily known for our fashion sense
at Google.

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:45.940
So this is.
[laughter]

00:00:45.940 --> 00:00:47.720
&gt;&gt;Garance: [laughing] This looks very good.

00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:50.850
&gt;&gt;Presenter: Thank you. I know she's talking
about me. Not so

00:00:50.850 --> 00:00:54.550
much some others. [laughter] So Garance, as
an illustrator, you came to

00:00:54.550 --> 00:00:58.600
your blog as a bit of a fashion outsider,
some might say. And now, you

00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:03.070
really positioned yourself, probably unintentionally,
as a really relatable fashion insider.

00:01:03.070 --> 00:01:06.330
Can you talk to us a little bit about that
evolution and how that

00:01:06.330 --> 00:01:07.330
happened.

00:01:07.330 --> 00:01:10.090
&gt;&gt;Garance: Yes, it's a long story. But I try
to make it not too

00:01:10.090 --> 00:01:18.171
long. I open my blog because I was frustrated.
I --

00:01:18.171 --> 00:01:23.270
after studying communication and working as
a -- how do

00:01:23.270 --> 00:01:27.030
you say PR in a cinema which was great but
not very

00:01:27.030 --> 00:01:30.259
fulfilling for me. I had that thing like,
"I want to be

00:01:30.259 --> 00:01:35.930
an artist. I'm frustrated. My life is okay,
but it's

00:01:35.930 --> 00:01:42.330
just okay. My dreams --" and so, I was like,
"okay, I'm

00:01:42.330 --> 00:01:47.380
26 or 27. It's the moment to do something,
because later

00:01:47.380 --> 00:01:49.649
is going to be too late, which is not true,
it's never

00:01:49.649 --> 00:01:53.409
too late. [laughter] But at that time, I was
like, "you have to do

00:01:53.409 --> 00:01:57.170
it now." So I dropped everything. I had a
very good

00:01:57.170 --> 00:02:00.119
friend support system, so I didn't really
feel alone. A

00:02:00.119 --> 00:02:03.759
lot of my friends were artists and everything.
So I

00:02:03.759 --> 00:02:07.649
started to teach myself illustration. That
was my dream.

00:02:07.649 --> 00:02:12.880
I had that dream of me, my studio, big windows
and like

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:17.650
illustrating all day. And so, of course in
the beginning

00:02:17.650 --> 00:02:21.550
my illustrations went horrible and I didn't
get any jobs

00:02:21.550 --> 00:02:25.110
and everything. But little by little by training
myself

00:02:25.110 --> 00:02:29.299
and getting kicked out of magazines and like
editors and

00:02:29.299 --> 00:02:32.310
everything, I ended up getting a few jobs
and started

00:02:32.310 --> 00:02:37.600
like working. And I should have been happy,
but I

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:41.700
realized that my dream was not that cool.
I mean, I was

00:02:41.700 --> 00:02:45.060
actually like alone all day, because illustration,
even

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:48.610
if you have big windows which I didn't have,
is very

00:02:48.610 --> 00:02:54.880
lonely job. And the thing is that I had to
send my

00:02:54.880 --> 00:02:56.709
illustration to an artistic director. The
artistic

00:02:56.709 --> 00:03:00.549
director would tell me, "Okay. This lady looks
good, but

00:03:00.549 --> 00:03:05.569
can you make her top more pink and her boobs
bigger. And

00:03:05.569 --> 00:03:08.500
that like this and she should be smiling."
Because I was

00:03:08.500 --> 00:03:11.641
not yet working for Vogue or anything. So
you know it

00:03:11.641 --> 00:03:14.420
could be more commercial work. And by the
time I would

00:03:14.420 --> 00:03:18.120
see my work printed in a magazine or a book,
it wasn't

00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:20.620
what I wanted. I thought it looked horrible.
So I was

00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:26.390
very frustrated. At that time, Scott the Sartorialist
--

00:03:26.390 --> 00:03:29.069
I didn't know him at that time, I knew that
blog and I

00:03:29.069 --> 00:03:32.819
was fascinated. Because first I had never
been to New

00:03:32.819 --> 00:03:36.000
York. At that time I was not living in Paris.
I was

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:41.110
living in the south of France. And I felt
very -- the

00:03:41.110 --> 00:03:43.110
only connection I had and at that time there
was really

00:03:43.110 --> 00:03:46.800
no Internet. The beginning. The only connection
to the

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:49.909
world was like through magazines. I would
always buy.

00:03:49.909 --> 00:03:54.250
like, a lot of magazines. Lots everywhere.
So I was

00:03:54.250 --> 00:03:59.060
watching that, "oh my God, this is crazy.
What's

00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:01.329
happening? I can be in New York. I can see
all these

00:04:01.329 --> 00:04:05.510
cool people that" -- and it inspired me to
open my blog.

00:04:05.510 --> 00:04:10.250
And so, what I told myself was, "I'm going
to give myself

00:04:10.250 --> 00:04:13.629
a last chance." It had been like two years
since I

00:04:13.629 --> 00:04:15.580
started dropping everything and started taking
on

00:04:15.580 --> 00:04:19.420
illustration. This is going to be my chance
to talk

00:04:19.420 --> 00:04:25.140
directly to the people without having an artistic
director changing my work. It's going to be

00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:28.290
a last
chance to try -- I mean, at that time I was

00:04:28.290 --> 00:04:33.070
taking too
long to illustrate. Like a week to do one

00:04:33.070 --> 00:04:38.970
illustration.
Illustration in a magazine is like 200 Euros.

00:04:38.970 --> 00:04:41.830
So, if you
take ten days to do that.

00:04:41.830 --> 00:04:44.280
&gt;&gt;Presenter: Yeah, it's not a lot of money.
[laughter]

00:04:44.280 --> 00:04:48.580
&gt;&gt; Garance: You're never going to get anywhere.
No big windows.

00:04:48.580 --> 00:04:51.850
So I was like, "I need to learn to draw more
fast. I'm

00:04:51.850 --> 00:04:54.510
going to open a blog and every day I'm going
to post

00:04:54.510 --> 00:04:57.360
something. It comes the weekend, I'm going
to give myself

00:04:57.360 --> 00:05:03.050
an hour because I have a life, you know, one
hour post on a

00:05:03.050 --> 00:05:06.250
blog. Try to be closer to people that have
their real

00:05:06.250 --> 00:05:11.830
feedback. And the only thing I told myself
was that I'm

00:05:11.830 --> 00:05:16.760
not going to say I live in Paris. Because
[laughing]

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:20.420
Because going to Paris to show my book -- because
at that

00:05:20.420 --> 00:05:23.610
time you would go with your book, you know,
your

00:05:23.610 --> 00:05:27.840
portfolio. Going each time people were like,
"oh, nice

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:29.830
work; that's cool. We're going to call you.
Oh, you

00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:37.590
don't live in Paris? [laughter] Oh, okay.
I'll call you. Bye. Never

00:05:37.590 --> 00:05:39.470
call back. Because there was really that thing
like --

00:05:39.470 --> 00:05:43.110
people, I think, even at that time we were
working with

00:05:43.110 --> 00:05:46.680
e-mail. Because when I started we were still
working

00:05:46.680 --> 00:05:50.470
with like scanning the stuff faxing the stuff.
Internet

00:05:50.470 --> 00:05:53.750
was starting. Working through e-mails and
everything.

00:05:53.750 --> 00:05:58.500
But they want to feel like you're here. You're
in the

00:05:58.500 --> 00:05:59.500
same.

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:00.500
&gt;&gt; Presenter: Even the fact that there's technology.

00:06:00.500 --> 00:06:03.530
&gt;&gt; Garance: You're in the same world as them.
I didn't know. I

00:06:03.530 --> 00:06:07.580
didn't belong because I was far -- so I was
like no way. Totally

00:06:07.580 --> 00:06:11.940
Parisian. So I was talking on my blog about
myself, never

00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:15.250
mentioning you know how where I was living.
Everything

00:06:15.250 --> 00:06:19.440
was a little vague. But you know. [laughter]
It worked out. And

00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:22.810
so, but of course, so what happened is that
when I opened

00:06:22.810 --> 00:06:28.430
my blog, I don't know -- it took off very
fast, because I

00:06:28.430 --> 00:06:31.080
first started publishing just illustrations
and then I

00:06:31.080 --> 00:06:34.850
realize I like to communicate and exchange
with people.

00:06:34.850 --> 00:06:37.600
And so, I started publishing texts and like
three weeks

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:41.690
later a magazine called me and said, "this
is special.

00:06:41.690 --> 00:06:43.650
We want to make a little story about it."
And so, I had

00:06:43.650 --> 00:06:49.400
like a little story in a French magazine,
L'Express, which is pretty

00:06:49.400 --> 00:06:54.240
big. And from that point, you know, I was
like

00:06:54.240 --> 00:06:56.380
legitimate and people would come to the blog
and the

00:06:56.380 --> 00:06:59.020
audience would grow. At that time I had like
2000

00:06:59.020 --> 00:07:00.020
readers.

00:07:00.020 --> 00:07:02.789
&gt;&gt; Presenter: After three weeks? After three
weeks? That's extraordinary.

00:07:02.789 --> 00:07:06.240
&gt;&gt; Garance: It was very, very fast. I think
what happened was that I was the first one

00:07:06.240 --> 00:07:12.080
to do that mix of fashion and like
telling stories about my life at the same

00:07:12.080 --> 00:07:17.520
time plus
illustration. And my blog was cute. It was

00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:20.140
really like --
&gt;&gt;Presenter: It still is cute, Garance

00:07:20.140 --> 00:07:22.820
[laughter]
&gt;&gt; Garance: But I really -- the design was

00:07:22.820 --> 00:07:26.150
as simple as it is
today so that you could see the images. So

00:07:26.150 --> 00:07:28.620
I think it's
a pleasure to come every day and see a new

00:07:28.620 --> 00:07:34.240
-- you know
what? At that time blogs were like -- people

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:36.210
didn't
really care. That's a blog. She's going to

00:07:36.210 --> 00:07:40.590
put that
image. With my -- you know -- and since the

00:07:40.590 --> 00:07:43.130
beginning I
was like I wanted to look good. And so, I

00:07:43.130 --> 00:07:46.061
think it's
easy to get. Even if they don't read, people

00:07:46.061 --> 00:07:47.990
just come
and check and see there's an illustration

00:07:47.990 --> 00:07:51.690
that's nice to see. So
it took off very fast like that. And it took

00:07:51.690 --> 00:07:54.450
off in
France, because France was very early with

00:07:54.450 --> 00:07:58.160
the blogging
thing. We really had the big movement. Looking

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:02.600
at
you because you're French. [laughter] And

00:08:02.600 --> 00:08:06.800
so, there was that
movement where like ten, 15 bloggers and we

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:09.900
were called
fashion bloggers, just because we were women

00:08:09.900 --> 00:08:13.530
and we were
talking about the things we talk about when

00:08:13.530 --> 00:08:16.670
we're with
friends. And so, you know I was called a fashion

00:08:16.670 --> 00:08:18.960
blogger. That's how it started.

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:21.870
&gt;&gt; Presenter: You and Scott -- so Scott Schuman
who, if you don't

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:27.250
know writes -- blogs The Sartorialist, which
is an amazing

00:08:27.250 --> 00:08:30.060
blog here in New York -- based largely in
New York.

00:08:30.060 --> 00:08:34.660
She's also in love with him. [laughter] That
smile is not just as a

00:08:34.660 --> 00:08:38.379
fan of his work. You guys were really at if
forefront of

00:08:38.379 --> 00:08:41.019
this. I think blogging has changed since you
guys came

00:08:41.019 --> 00:08:42.959
on the scene. Especially fashion blogging.
There's a

00:08:42.959 --> 00:08:45.750
lot of people who are chronicling daily outfit
choices.

00:08:45.750 --> 00:08:49.779
So what do you think of that evolution. It's
really a

00:08:49.779 --> 00:08:53.620
trend, if you can call it a trend since we're
talking about fashion, that you guys really

00:08:53.620 --> 00:08:54.620
started.

00:08:54.620 --> 00:08:59.269
&gt;&gt; Garance: Yeah, I think it's funny. For
a long time, I think

00:08:59.269 --> 00:09:02.230
blogging was really about -- it was more like
forums.

00:09:02.230 --> 00:09:04.490
You know where you want to communicate with
people and

00:09:04.490 --> 00:09:10.889
share your stuff but not really make -- it
was not a way

00:09:10.889 --> 00:09:14.810
to be famous. You know, it was not a way -- you
didn't

00:09:14.810 --> 00:09:17.839
make money or be famous. It was more like
a way to

00:09:17.839 --> 00:09:21.810
communicate and make a new circle of friends,
right. And

00:09:21.810 --> 00:09:26.459
so, I mean, for a long time. My blog is like
five years

00:09:26.459 --> 00:09:30.570
and a half. I think for like two years -- of
course I

00:09:30.570 --> 00:09:35.170
started to see, like, I had, like, story in
a magazine and

00:09:35.170 --> 00:09:37.550
another one. So I could see that there was
something

00:09:37.550 --> 00:09:39.209
happening. But for a long time it was more
like -- it

00:09:39.209 --> 00:09:45.330
was a community thing. And with Scott -- Scott
started

00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:49.220
working on style.com and I started to work
with Vogue.

00:09:49.220 --> 00:09:52.569
Things like that. And I think it became clear
that it

00:09:52.569 --> 00:09:58.199
was a great way to make self-promotion and
at that time a

00:09:58.199 --> 00:10:02.540
new generation of bloggers arrived who, you
know, would

00:10:02.540 --> 00:10:06.670
more maybe think of how could I get myself
out in this world

00:10:06.670 --> 00:10:09.220
which is cool, you know, but how can I show
my work, how

00:10:09.220 --> 00:10:15.600
can I show myself? So that was a second -- how
do you

00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:16.600
say?

00:10:16.600 --> 00:10:17.600
&gt;&gt; Presenter: Wave.

00:10:17.600 --> 00:10:18.600
&gt;&gt; Garance: Yeah, second wave of bloggers.

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:23.100
&gt;&gt; Presenter: So do you think that bloggers
such as yourself and Scott, with

00:10:23.100 --> 00:10:25.000
the kind of influence that you've had in the
industry

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.410
which is quite tremendous and I'd like to
talk about that

00:10:27.410 --> 00:10:30.499
in a minute, too. Do you think there's room
for bloggers

00:10:30.499 --> 00:10:33.810
to have that type of influence again in the
industry -- in

00:10:33.810 --> 00:10:34.810
fashion.

00:10:34.810 --> 00:10:38.560
&gt;&gt;Garance: I'm sure there is. I mean, for
me it's just the

00:10:38.560 --> 00:10:45.290
beginning. The only thing is that what is
interesting --

00:10:45.290 --> 00:10:48.749
the fact that I come from that far away place
that is the

00:10:48.749 --> 00:10:55.759
past. [giggles] And is that I really started
doing the blog for

00:10:55.759 --> 00:11:00.019
reasons that were, like, I want to be free.
I want to be

00:11:00.019 --> 00:11:04.170
able to talk freely. I want to be able to
share with

00:11:04.170 --> 00:11:09.560
people that -- without the filter -- and Scott
was

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:12.810
exactly the same. I think he was frustrated
because he

00:11:12.810 --> 00:11:15.699
would see those people in the street and what
he saw in

00:11:15.699 --> 00:11:19.399
magazines was totally different. So he made
like that

00:11:19.399 --> 00:11:23.130
&gt;&gt;Presenter: that connection

00:11:23.130 --> 00:11:27.170
&gt;&gt;Garance: that link between the people that
were reading magazines. So

00:11:27.170 --> 00:11:30.199
you could see -- there was really--it was
really

00:11:30.199 --> 00:11:33.810
expressing something that was missing. Whereas
now I

00:11:33.810 --> 00:11:40.080
think it's becoming a real business, right?
And so, I

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:45.910
think -- what I still feel that way. I still
feel like I

00:11:45.910 --> 00:11:49.560
want to be in places where other people are
not -- so I

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:53.441
want to be where, you know, I don't care about
going to a

00:11:53.441 --> 00:11:56.490
show and saying "woo, it's wonderful". I say
it sometimes

00:11:56.490 --> 00:11:59.269
when it's great, but it's not my mission.
I mean,

00:11:59.269 --> 00:12:02.790
magazines are here for that. Now other bloggers
do that

00:12:02.790 --> 00:12:05.720
very well. But I really -- I'm not interested.
I don't

00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:09.449
want to be bored by myself. I'm my first reader.
And

00:12:09.449 --> 00:12:14.209
even if I'm invited to do stuff. Also because
I started

00:12:14.209 --> 00:12:17.810
like when I was older, so I think I have.

00:12:17.810 --> 00:12:18.810
&gt;&gt; Presenter: 26.
[laughter]

00:12:18.810 --> 00:12:22.990
&gt;&gt; Garance: But yeah I opened my blog when
I was around 30. So

00:12:22.990 --> 00:12:27.459
it's like I feel like I've been frustrated
long enough

00:12:27.459 --> 00:12:29.910
that I don't want to fall back into that thing
and be

00:12:29.910 --> 00:12:34.200
that blog where you go and you're like, "who
is she

00:12:34.200 --> 00:12:37.850
talking for? You know, is she talking for
that brand,

00:12:37.850 --> 00:12:40.010
that advertiser or whatever?" I'm really talking
for

00:12:40.010 --> 00:12:43.069
people that are like me. I hope. That's what
I want to do what I

00:12:43.069 --> 00:12:45.439
want to keep on doing.

00:12:45.439 --> 00:12:48.279
&gt;&gt; Presenter: Do you think there's anything
particular about the

00:12:48.279 --> 00:12:51.430
moment when you started, since it was really
at the forefront

00:12:51.430 --> 00:12:57.320
of this whole blogging trend, that led to
your success or

00:12:57.320 --> 00:13:00.100
sort of helped kind of propel you.

00:13:00.100 --> 00:13:02.920
&gt;&gt; Garance: It's weird. We were trying to
talk about what I was

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:08.009
going to say today and earlier. And I was
like I think

00:13:08.009 --> 00:13:13.180
the thing that I'm still not really -- like,
realizing,

00:13:13.180 --> 00:13:16.220
you know, is that people get attached to a
personality.

00:13:16.220 --> 00:13:18.620
For a long time I was, like, what do people
like about my

00:13:18.620 --> 00:13:22.700
blog? Is it the writing? I'm very goofy when
I write. For me, I am not a writer.

00:13:22.700 --> 00:13:26.319
Is it the illustrations? Is it the photo?
What exactly

00:13:26.319 --> 00:13:31.749
is it? And I think now I have enough experience
that I

00:13:31.749 --> 00:13:35.019
can realize okay maybe it's just a personality.
You

00:13:35.019 --> 00:13:38.160
know, it's a big picture. It's like a little
bit of

00:13:38.160 --> 00:13:41.999
everything. And so, I think that's -- this
and the fact

00:13:41.999 --> 00:13:46.579
that my personality is being very easy. You
know, I talk

00:13:46.579 --> 00:13:51.990
about any kind of women's problem and you
know, I don't

00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:52.990
hide anything.

00:13:52.990 --> 00:13:55.069
&gt;&gt; Presenter: You're very candid on your blog.
[laughter]

00:13:55.069 --> 00:13:59.279
&gt;&gt;Garance: I'm not trying to say that I'm
perfect. And I think

00:13:59.279 --> 00:14:01.199
that's what was missing. In magazines, I would
read

00:14:01.199 --> 00:14:05.209
interviews of celebrities. Wow, she really
wakes up at

00:14:05.209 --> 00:14:10.199
five and drinks water with lemon inside and
then she does

00:14:10.199 --> 00:14:12.839
yoga before, you know, going.

00:14:12.839 --> 00:14:15.470
&gt;&gt; Presenter: She doesn't exercise either.
[laughter]

00:14:15.470 --> 00:14:20.490
